			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I have used this and it does not give you mana in <BR>
return.  It simply drains a portion of the target's <BR>
mana away.  Hard to &quot;see&quot; this occuring so I usually <BR>
just trust to fate and throw it in now and then if <BR>
I'm fighting a casting mob.  I don't use it that often<BR>
though.  Take something like a spec.  A spec will <BR>
sometimes pause mid melee to try to cast on ya.  Well<BR>
draining its mana sounds nice, but recall while the <BR>
spec is casting it ain't swinging it's scythe, so if <BR>
you resist the spell you've effectively escaped a round<BR>
or two of melee.  Draining mana may make the spec quit<BR>
casting and decide to concentrate on spilling your guts<BR>
instead.  That is, sometimes a mob casting ain't the <BR>
worst thing in the world. <BR>
<BR>
Now other mobs, I'd definitely want to drain.  Mobs that<BR>
cast huge AE damage spells I'd much rather have swinging <BR>
at me or my pet for 60 or 70 per hit than casting 200 damage<BR>
nukes on my party.  It just depends on the mob and what<BR>
their spells do.  
